Nigerians with means of livelihood have been challenged to imbibe the culture of tax payment as part of measures aimed at the socio-economic transformation of the country, in line with the policy thrust of the present administration. The permanent secretary, Ministry of Interior, Barr. Georgina Ehuriah, made the challenge  when she played host to  the Society of Women in Taxation (SWIT), the female arm of the Chartered Institute of Taxation in Nigeria, (CITN). Ehuriah who stressed that the role of SWIT has become more challenging, considering  the spate of insecurity in some parts of the country as well as the decline in revenue generation from oil, called on them to create more awareness and sensitisation on the issue of commitment to tax payment by Nigerians to enable the realisation of the government’s policy thrust which is anchored on security and economy  amongst others. This is even as the permanent secretary also assured that the ministry would continue to collaborate with government agencies and non-governmental organisations with a view to improving internal security and citizenship integrity in line with its mandate. She promised that government will continue to provide the basic infrastructure that will bring about socio-economic development, public safety and security of Nigerians, adding that there is an urgent need for the diversification of the economy so as to meet the present economic realities. The permanent secretary who stated that tax payment was part of the constitutional responsibility of Nigerians, described tax evasion as a criminal offence and advised those who are indulging in the habit to show patriotism by ensuring that they pay their taxes as at when due. Earlier, the national president, Society of Women in Taxation (SWIT), Hajia Kudirat Abdulhameed said that they were in the ministry as part of their sensitisation and awareness campaign on tax payment by all Nigerians who have a means of livelihood. Kudirat noted that women have a critical role to play in ensuring safety and security in all nations, adding that SWIT has been involved in a number of activities aimed at promoting the ideals and mandates of CITN as well as carrying out projects that greatly impact positively on members of the Society. 